long_desc.thetext: Felix could you have a look at https://git.eclipse.org/r/#/c/7450/ ? It's a test I prepared basing on your comment 0. Apparently I over-simplified the test as it passes. Nevertheless it should be easier now to adjust it to what you're experiencing. A failing test would be a perfect starter.
I can provide you with example projects and specify an Eclipse configuration which produces the problem, would that be acceptable?

(In reply to comment #2) > I can provide you with example projects and specify an Eclipse configuration > which produces the problem, would that be acceptable?
Yes, please. As small example as possible.

Created attachment 220469 Maven projects
I have been able to reproduce this issue with Eclipse 3.7.2 and 4.2.0. You would need such an Eclipse distribution and install m2eclipse (http://download.eclipse.org/technology/m2e/releases ) and ObjectAid (http://www.objectaid.com/update). ObjectAid also requires the GEF. Since the issue occurs with the ObjectAid Sequence Diagram, you would also have to get an evaluation license for that (see http://www.objectaid.com/install-license).
Attached is a stripped down version of the a Maven multi-module project as I received it (gwtck.zip). It should be built with Maven on the command line and imported into Eclipse (File > Import > Existing Maven Projects).
For Maven to work, you should replace (temporarily) your Maven settings.xml (in your user folder or wherever) with the one supplied in the .m2 folder of the attached ZIP file. Note, all files are UTF-8 encoded. Make sure you start Eclipse with -Dfile.encoding=utf8 (in eclipse.ini).
To reproduce the issue, open the sequence diagram /gwtck-client/docs/toggleable-grid.useq. Right-click on the message 'setInput' and select 'Add Called Operations'. You will get an 'Unhandled event loop exception' in the Error Log view as described above.
Can you reproduce the problem with info I provided?
Can you please take a look. As a first step, please confirm if you are able to reproduce this.
I can reproduce this with 4.2. And the extra parameter you mentioned is the receiver for the constructor, which is nothing but the containing class. Will see what's going on.

Created attachment 220960 Testcase
Test case for the scenario described in comment #0.
From my initial investigation, there are two issues at hand: 1. The Util#getUnresolvedJavaElement() includes the receiver to the inner type's constructor parameter list. I am not sure if we really require that.
2. org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.MethodBinding#getJavaElement() Call to the getUnresolvedJavaElement() returns the parameter with 'Q' prefix (meaning the parameters are unresolved). But the subsequent call to JavaElement#resolved(binding) doesn't bother to mark the parameters are resolved (convert the 'Q's to 'L's)
This is resulting in the method not being picked from the java model cache.
Jay, is this a regression ? Can you find out the earliest version with the bug ?

(In reply to comment #9) > Jay, is this a regression ? Can you find out the earliest version with > the bug ?
By running my test against R3_6 and R3_7, I see this bug has been around for a long time. But I can't confirm it with the steps given in comment #0 because of objectAid license issues.
Felix, would you be able to test with the older eclipse releases and confirm my finding?

(In reply to comment #8) > From my initial investigation, there are two issues at hand:
What I stated was not entirely true. The real problem is that we are constructing and including the receiver parameter even for static inner types. I will post a patch soon.

Created attachment 221015 Fix + Test
This patch makes sure that static inner types don't get receivers for constructors. I have tested this fixes use case mentioned in comment #0.
Do you still need me to look into older Eclipse versions? What is the nature of your ObjectAid licensing issues?
Released the fix in HEAD here: http://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.core.git/commit/?id=461abfc9125d1c5c723168274721daaac193d010

(In reply to comment #13) > Do you still need me to look into older Eclipse versions? > What is the nature of your ObjectAid licensing issues?
No, that is not required anymore. But you can download the next N or I build and confirm it works.
